   <text>
      <body>
         <head>To <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0762.xml"/>Dorothy Furly</persName></head>
         <opener><placeName>London</placeName><lb/><date when="1759-08-19">August 19, 1759</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>My Dear Sister,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p><pb n="171"/>The observing that rule might prevent abundance of mischief. I wish others
            would observe it as well as you. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2127.xml"/>Thomas
               Walsh</persName> was a good and a wise man, yet there were some circumstances, not
            commonly known, which easily account for the darkness he went through before he went to
               paradise.<note place="foot" n="1"><persName><ref target="/persons/pers2127.xml"
                  />Thomas Walsh</persName>&apos;s death in <date when="1759-04">Apr. 1759</date> in
                  <placeName>Bristol</placeName> (while <persName><ref
                     target="/persons/pers0762.xml"/>Furly</persName> was in nearby
                  <placeName>Clifton</placeName>) was accompanied with significant suffering and
               spiritual struggle; see <hi rend="italic">EMP</hi>, 3:258–68.</note></p>
         <p>I hope you have <hi rend="italic">talked</hi> with <persName><ref
                  target="/persons/pers0114.xml"/>Cornelius Bastable</persName> as well as heard him
            preach. He is an uncommon monument of the power of grace, strengthening the
            understanding as well as renewing the heart. For so weak a head and so bad a temper as
            he once had I do not know among all our preachers.<note place="foot" n="2"
                     ><persName><ref target="/persons/pers0114.xml"/>Cornelius Bastable</persName>
               (c. <date from="1725" to="1775">1725–75</date>), apparently a native of
                  <placeName>Middlezoy, Somerset</placeName>, began &apos;exhorting&apos; in <date
                  when="1747">1747</date> and came to <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                  />JW</persName>&apos;s attention as a promising prospective preacher in <date
                  when="1748-07">Sept. 1748</date>. He appears in the Minutes as a
               &apos;probationary helper&apos; in <date when="1750">1750</date>, but did not advance
               to the regular <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerancy</seg>, likely because he married
                  <persName>Catherine Stockdale</persName> (<date from="1726" to="1786"
                  >1726–86</date>) in <placeName>Cork</placeName> in <date when="1752">1752</date>
               (see 10:205, 237 in this edn.). The couple was currently living in the
                  <placeName>Bristol</placeName> area.</note></p>
         <p>Probably the difference between you and others lies in words chiefly. All who expect to
            be sanctified at all expect to be sanctified <hi rend="italic">by faith</hi>. But
            meantime they know that faith will not be given but to them that <hi rend="italic"
               >obey</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Remotely</hi>, therefore, the blessing depends on our
            works, although <hi rend="italic">immediately</hi> on simple faith.</p>
         <p>Enjoy while you may the advantage which I had once, and shall have again when God sees
            best. I am,</p>
         <closer><signed>Your affectionate brother,<lb/><persName>J.
            Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
         <postscript>
            <p><pb n="172"/>Certainly <hi rend="italic">you</hi> may say to <hi rend="italic"
                  >me</hi> whatever you have a mind, either by writing or speaking.</p>
         </postscript>
      </body>
   </text>
